04452nam a2200589Ia 9780691268392DE-B159720240602123719.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||240602t20242011nju    fo  d z      eng d  a97806912683927 a10.1515/97806912683922doi  a(DE-B1597)694810  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  anjucUS-NJ 4aHM548b.S7413 2011 7aSOC0260002bisacsh04a306.30922221 aSteiner, Philippe, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aDurkheim and the Birth of Economic Sociology /cPhilippe Steiner. 1aPrinceton, NJ : bPrinceton University Press, c[2024] 4c©2011  a1 online resource (264 p.) :b3 line illus. 5 tables.  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tTranslator’s Note -- tIntroduction -- tCHAPTER ONE Durkheim and the Critique of Political Economy -- tCHAPTER TWO Politics, Economy and Religion -- tCHAPTER THREE Simiand and the Critique of Political Economy -- tCHAPTER FOUR Positive Political Economy, or Durkheimian Economic Sociology -- tCHAPTER FIVE Religion and Economy MAUSS AND THE SECOND DURKHEIMIAN PROGRAMME -- tCHAPTER SIX The Encounter between Two Programmes -- tCHAPTER SEVEN Sociology of Economic Knowledge and the Critique of Political Economy -- tCHAPTER EIGHT From Religious Rationalisation to Rational Education -- tConclusion -- tReferences -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aAn illuminating account of the development of Durkheim's economic sociologyÉmile Durkheim's work has traditionally been viewed as a part of sociology removed from economics. Rectifying this perception, Durkheim and the Birth of Economic Sociology is the first book to provide an in-depth look at the contributions made to economic sociology by Durkheim and his followers. Philippe Steiner demonstrates the relevance of economic factors to sociology and shows how the Durkheimians inform today's economic systems.Steiner argues that there are two stages in Durkheim's approach to the economy—a sociological critique of political economy and a sociology of economic knowledge. In his early works, Durkheim critiques economists and their categories, and tries to analyze the division of labor from a social rather than economic perspective. From the mid-1890s onward, Durkheim's preoccupations shifted to questions of religion and the sociology of knowledge. Durkheim's disciples, such as Maurice Halbwachs and François Simiand, synthesized and elaborated on Durkheim's first-stage arguments, while his ideas on religion and the economy were taken up by Marcel Mauss. Steiner indicates that the ways in which the Durkheimians rooted the sociology of economic knowledge in the educational system allows for an invaluable perspective on the role of economics in modern society, similar to the perspective offered by Max Weber's work.Recognizing the power of the Durkheimian approach, Durkheim and the Birth of Economic Sociology assesses the effect of this important thinker and his successors on one of the most active fields in contemporary sociology.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 02. Jun 2024) 0aDurkheimian school of sociology. 0aEconomicsxSociological aspects. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Sociology / General.2bisacsh1 aTribe, Keith, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb40uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/9780691268392?locatt=mode:legacy40uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780691268392423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780691268392/original  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_CL_SN  aEBA_EBACKALL  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_SN  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESSHALL  aEBA_PPALL  aEBA_SSHALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles